To strengthen the risk management capabilities of the Municipal Government and enable it to manage its vulnerabilities in the event of disruptive events, we recommend that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) institutionalize the PSCP by creating a working group that will perform the following activities:
to conduct risk assessment;
to identify critical processes and functions;
to determine scenarios that may disrupt normal operation;
to conduct risk analysis and impact analysis;
to formulate the PSCP based on the identified risks on critical processes and functions and its related steps to be followed to eliminate, if not mitigate, the impact of the determined disruptions following the prescribed template and be guided by the PSCP guidebook; and
to submit plan to the MDRRMO for review, to the LCE for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP.
We also recommend that Management should improve their monitoring of operational requirements like the submission of PSCP.

We recommended to Management the following:
The Inventory Committee conduct complete physical inventory of all property and submit the results thereof to the Agency Auditor;
The General Services Officer prepare the Inventory and Inspection Report on all unserviceable properties that will be identified during the count and facilitate their immediate disposal to prevent further deterioration and decrease in salvage values;
The Municipal Accountant make the reconciliation between the results of the physical count and the property records; and,
The Municipal Mayor issue an executive order creating an Inventory Committee consistent with COA Circular No. 2020-006 who shall be momentarily relieved of all their regular duties to devote their full time in the conduct of the physical inventory taking until the same is completed.

